If the EXECUTION PLAN declares `## Work Units` or `## Parallel Plan`, dispatch your own sub-agents to carry out the parallel work in dependency order within each unit's declared `Directories:`; if your runtime has no sub-agents, execute the same units sequentially in `[unit-ID]` order. Ralph Workflow exposes no coordination command for plan work — dispatch is entirely your job. Even without declared work units, you may fan out read-only sub-agents for information gathering and run independent, non-overlapping steps concurrently; never let two sub-agents edit the same file.

Native file and shell tools are disabled in this brokered fallback; native orchestration tools (sub-agents/tasks, skills, todo tracking, web fetch/search) remain enabled — use them whenever they help. Use `{{EXEC_TOOL_NAME}}` for shell commands and `{{REPORT_PROGRESS_TOOL_NAME}}` to report status instead of native tools like `bash`.

## Development result artifact contract

You MUST submit a `development_result` artifact before declaring completion.
The complete grammar lives in `.agent/artifact-formats/development_result.md`.

Submit one native-markdown document:

1. Use `type: development_result` and `status: completed|partial` frontmatter,
   then `## Summary` (exactly one item), `## Files Changed` (one item per
   file), and `## Plan Items Proven` — one `- [S-n] <proof>` item per plan
   step (or one `- [unit-ID] <proof>` item per work unit), the bracketed ID
   copied EXACTLY from the plan. When analysis feedback exists, add
   `## Analysis Items Addressed` with one item per prior `## How To Fix`
   entry, reusing that entry's stable ID.
2. Submit with ralph_submit_md_artifact (`artifact_type="development_result"`,
   `content` = the full markdown document — never JSON).
3. If the submit tool is unavailable, write the same complete document to
   `.agent/tmp/development_result.md` instead.

